first Im interested in seeing the population data variance

ggplot(aes(x = poptotal), data=midwest) + geom_histogram()
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

this view is a little messy. let me modify the x axis

ggplot(aes(x = poptotal), data=midwest) + geom_histogram(bins=100) + scale_x_continuous(limits = c(0, 100000))
## Warning: Removed 85 rows containing non-finite values (stat_bin).

I can see from this data that there is nothing above 100000 as far as population. next i wonder if area relates to the population

ggplot(aes(area, poptotal), data=midwest) + geom_point()

Interesting, but there are clearly some outliers. I wonder who is the datapoint with the excessively large population

largePop <- subset(midwest, poptotal > 5000000)
largePop$county
## [1] "COOK"

based on county this is has to be Chicago. Lets exclude that outlier and take another look

ggplot(aes(area, poptotal), data=subset(midwest, poptotal < 5000000)) + geom_point()

Even excluding the large datapoint there doesnt seem to be a clear correlation between land area and population as you might think

taking a more abstract view at just population density:

ggplot(midwest, aes(popdensity)) + geom_histogram(binwidth=500)

interesting, but I want to hone in on the densest area

ggplot(midwest, aes(popdensity)) + geom_histogram(binwidth=500) + scale_x_continuous(limits = c(0,12500), breaks = c(2000, 4000, 6000, 8000, 10000, 12000))
## Warning: Removed 17 rows containing non-finite values (stat_bin).

a little clearer where the activity is here, but I want to see the median (green) and mean (blue) as well

ggplot(midwest, aes(popdensity)) + geom_histogram(binwidth=500) + scale_x_continuous(limits = c(0,12500), breaks = c(2000, 4000, 6000, 8000, 10000, 12000)) + geom_vline(xintercept = 1156.21, color="green", linetype="longdash") + geom_vline(xintercept = 3097.74, color="blue", linetype="longdash") + labs(title="Population Density in the Midwest",x="Density",y="Count")

Next Im interested to see if theres a positive correlation between increased poverty (percentage wise) as population increases

ggplot(midwest, aes(percpovertyknown, poptotal)) + geom_point()

Lets docus in more on the high in with the highest concentration

coef(lm(poptotal~percpovertyknown, data=midwest))
##      (Intercept) percpovertyknown 
##      -277009.888         3842.438
ggplot(midwest, aes(percpovertyknown, poptotal)) + geom_point() +geom_smooth(method="lm", se = FALSE) + scale_x_continuous(limits = c(95, 100))
## Warning: Removed 55 rows containing non-finite values (stat_smooth).
## Warning: Removed 55 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

Generally speaking you do seem to see greater instances of increased population as you move toward higher perc poverty. There may be a loose correlation, lets do a correlation test to see how strong

cor.test(midwest$percpovertyknown, midwest$poptotal)
## 
##  Pearson's product-moment correlation
## 
## data:  midwest$percpovertyknown and midwest$poptotal
## t = 0.73956, df = 435, p-value = 0.46
## alternative hypothesis: true correlation is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -0.05856266  0.12881319
## sample estimates:
##       cor 
## 0.0354367

At best its a very weak positive correlation coversely Id expect the percent in poverty to decrease as percent college educated increases.

coef(lm(percpovertyknown~percollege, data=midwest))
## (Intercept)  percollege 
##  99.2458309  -0.1168716
ggplot(midwest, aes(percollege, percpovertyknown)) + geom_point() + geom_smooth(method="lm", se=FALSE) + labs(title="Poverty as Educated Population Increases",x="Percent of pop College Educated",y="Percent of pop Poverty")

Indeed it appears there is a noticable negative correlation associated with college educated populations and povery. The cor-test backs that up:

cor.test(midwest$percpovertyknown, midwest$percollege)

Im noticing that theres 2 parameters: percpovertynkown and percbelowpoverty I want a total picture of poverty so I want to combine those values in to a new parameter totalpercpoverty

midwest <- transform(midwest, totalpercpoverty = percpovertyknown + percbelowpoverty)

In hindsight this doesnt appear to be how the percentages work, need to clear this column

midwest$totalpercpoverty <- NULL

This is a fun exercise. Its surprisingly difficult to find general data out in the wild thats moderately well cleaned. The midwest dataset is interesting enough and well munged as part of the ggplot package. One of the most difficult things Im finding is determining the most useful visualization type. In some places line bar and scatter visualizations all provide interesting accounts of the same data. One of the most interesting features of this dataset is its insight into poverty, it could be extremely useful to get insight into common precursors of poverty. However the only other real useful data points are around education and percentage of minorities. I suspect there are many other possible causes for poverty so the dataset isnt quite as useful as it could be. Additional info such as crime rates in these counties could prove extremely valuable.
